@node sect0 "Name"
z81, xz81 - ZX81 and ZX80 emulators for the Linux console and X    
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
 @{b}z81/xz81@{ub} [@{b}-hilLosSTuV@{ub}] [@{b}-a@{ub} @{i}sound_addon_type@{ui}] [@{b}-p@{ub} @{i}printout.pbm@{ui}] [@{b}-r@{ub} @{i}refresh_rate@{ui}] [@{i}filename.p@{ui}]@{i}@{ui}     


@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
z81 is a Sinclair ZX81 (TS1000) and ZX80 emulator using svgalib. It supports most programs and games, the ZX81's pseudo-high-res mode, the ZX Printer, and both kinds of sound (`normal' and AY-based addons). It saves and loads programs in Xtender's `.P' format, but can load `.81' format files if they are suitably renamed. xz81 is a version of z81 for X. 

Both emulate a 16k ZX81 by default; to get a 1k ZX81, use the `-u' option. To emulate a ZX80, use the `-o' option. 

For the most faithful ZX81 emulation which z81 can manage, try e.g. `z81 -sLSVr 1'. But since that's not very useful (you can't load or save anything and the sound is very annoying), a more practical `best' emulation is e.g. `z81 -Vr 1'. 

If you want to transfer old ZX81 programs from tape, try @{i}zx81get@{ui}(1).    


@endnode

@node sect3 "Options"


· @{b}-a@{ub} @{lindent 3}
enable AY-3-8910/8912-based sound addon support. There were a few different AY-based sound addons released for the ZX81, so you also have to specify the addon type with one of the following (only two currently supported): @{lindent 6}
@{lindent 3}

· @{i}q@{ui} @{lindent 6}
Quicksilva sound board (as used by their Asteroids, Invaders, and Defender) @{lindent 3}

· @{i}z@{ui} @{lindent 6}
Bi-Pak's Zon X-81 @{lindent 3}

You can also enable ACB stereo (channel A on left only, B on right only, C on both `in the middle') by adding an @{i}s@{ui} suffix, e.g. `-a qs'. @{lindent 0}




· @{b}-h@{ub} @{lindent 3}
gives help on command line options. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-i@{ub} @{lindent 3}
invert the screen, giving a white-on-black display. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-l@{ub} @{lindent 3}
boot directly into the LOAD "" file selector. (If you press Space to abort in this case, it exits the emulator.) See the note below about @{i}filename.p@{ui} for the limitations of auto-loading like this. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-L@{ub} @{lindent 3}
disable LOAD hook. (Not terribly useful.) @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-o@{ub} @{lindent 3}
emulate an `old ROM' machine, i.e. a ZX80. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-p@{ub} @{lindent 3}
enable ZX Printer support. The printout is written as a PBM format picture to the specified file. (Most picture viewers/converters can handle PBM files.) @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-r@{ub} @{lindent 3}
specifies how often the screen is redrawn, in 1/50th-sec `frames'. A value of 1 would redraw every frame, 2 would redraw every other frame, etc. The default value is 2 in both versions. The screen is updated incrementally, so the default setting should be reasonable on just about any machine, for most programs. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-s@{ub} @{lindent 3}
enable VSYNC-based sound support. This is essentially a less-noisy version of what you'd hear through the TV. You probably don't want to enable this unless you have a specific need for it, as it makes an annoying hum in SLOW mode. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-S@{ub} @{lindent 3}
disable SAVE hook. Useful if you want to hear what SAVE does when sound is enabled. :-) (Just don't expect it to be saved as a file!) @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-T@{ub} @{lindent 3}
toggle the leftmost bit of characters generated by the ULA (mainly for debugging, but also useful for checking the display's `shape'). @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-u@{ub} @{lindent 3}
emulate an unexpanded machine, e.g. a 1k ZX81. The default for both machines is to have 16k of RAM. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}-V@{ub} @{lindent 3}
emulate VSYNC visuals - the black screen when busy in FAST mode, the patterns you get when you LOAD or SAVE on the real machine, and the little flicker you get when typing in a program line. (This tends to be a bit annoying when typing in a program, which is why this is disabled by default.) @{lindent 0}

· @{i}filename.p@{ui} @{lindent 3}
specifies a program to load. (Whether it auto-runs or not depends on how it was saved - just like on the real ZX81, the save command has to be run as part of the program for the resulting .P file to auto-run. Most .P files you'll come across will auto-run, though.) @{lindent 0}

Note that the auto-loading feature is not supported when emulating a ZX80, or a 1k ZX81. On those you have to do a LOAD command manually.    


@endnode

@node sect4 "Keys and Key Mapping"


· @{i}Esc@{ui} @{lindent 3}
reset the emulator. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}F1@{ui} @{lindent 3}
display a help screen showing the ZX81 (or ZX80) keyboard layout. Note that you can still type while this help screen is displayed (the emulated machine is still running), and to return to normal you must use @{i}F1@{ui} again. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}F10@{ui} @{lindent 3}
quit z81/xz81. You can also quit (when emulating a ZX81) with `LOAD " STOP "', where `STOP' is the keyword given by shift-A rather than `stop' typed out. @{lindent 0}

The alphanumeric and `.' keys are mapped as-is to the ZX81 (or ZX80) keys, with other mapped keys being: 



· @{i}Space@{ui} @{lindent 3}
emulated as break/space @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Shift@{ui} or @{i}Ctrl@{ui} @{lindent 3}
emulated as shift (Alt/Meta is similarly mapped on xz81) @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Enter@{ui} @{lindent 3}
emulated as newline @{lindent 0}

No other keys are mapped. If you can't remember how to get things like INKEY$ on a ZX81 keyboard, you'd better check out the help screen. (If you can't remember how to get INKEY$ on a @{i}ZX80@{ui} keyboard, that's not too surprising. :-)) 

A list of keys applicable when using the file selector is given in the @{b}FILE SELECTOR KEYS@{ub} section below. 

xz81 has a curious problem with shifts. If you use the real shift key, you seem to get incorrect results with the number keys (other keys being ok). Until this is fixed, use either control or alt/meta as shift - these work for all keys.    


@endnode

@node sect5 "the Emulated Zx81 or Zx80"
For those with hazy memories :-), the delay when a 16k ZX81 boots is normal (most of this time is devoted to enlarging the display file, try running with `-T' to see this in action), not some problem with the emulator. You can only avoid this delay by auto-loading a program; see @{b}OPTIONS@{ub} above. That apart, the emulated machine loads/saves programs with the LOAD and SAVE commands as usual. For example, `SAVE "FOO"' saves `foo.p' in the current directory. An extension to this is that if you do `LOAD ""' you get a file selector which lets you choose which file to load, navigating between directories if needed. (The last dir visited in this way (initially the current directory) is also the dir used for subsequent non-interactive LOAD/SAVE operations.) 

At least, the above applies when emulating a ZX81. In ZX80 mode, things are complicated by the fact that the ZX80 didn't support filenames. The LOAD and SAVE commands are just plain `LOAD' and `SAVE'. So I'm afraid that, for the time being at least, the emulated ZX80 can only load or save a file called `zx80prog.p'. 

Unless you use the `-V' option, there's no visual indication of FAST mode - the emulator simply keeps displaying the last SLOW mode frame. Even with `-V', you get a black screen rather than the `noisy' screen the real thing would give. 

The PBM written for printer output is updated whenever a new line of characters is printed, but you shouldn't move or delete the file until you exit the emulator (it's ok to read or copy it, of course).    


@endnode

@node sect6 "File Selector Keys"
Most of the keys available in the file selector are shown onscreen, but since some aren't (no room), here's a full list: 

· @{i}q@{ui} @{lindent 3}
move cursor up. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}a@{ui} @{lindent 3}
move cursor down. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Shift-q@{ui} @{lindent 3}
move cursor up a page. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Shift-a@{ui} @{lindent 3}
move cursor down a page. @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Enter@{ui} @{lindent 3}
load the file currently selected (or change to the directory). @{lindent 0}

· @{i}Space@{ui} @{lindent 3}
exit without loading. @{lindent 0}

Note that for `shifted' keys above, you can use anything the emulated ZX81 would consider a shift, including e.g. Ctrl. But unlike the emulated ZX81, the keys will auto-repeat if you hold them down.    


@endnode

@node sect7 "Bugs"
Some hi-res displays (all of which seem to be the `true hi-res' ones rather than the more common pseudo-hi-res type) aren't displayed properly - they kind of wrap around the screen. Also, true hi-res displays depend on very precise timing at the sub-instruction level, and wouldn't currently work in any case. Overscanned displays (e.g. QS Defender) tend to be larger than the screen area normally displayed, which can be awkward. 

The emulated ZX80 may have some problems, especially as I've never used a real ZX80 and wouldn't necessarily notice. But in particular, while doing `SAVE' as a command works, doing `SAVE' from within a program seems to result in the program being corrupted. 

The ZX80's display is shifted right quite noticeably. There seems to be some sort of VSYNC-related timing problem, but I'm not sure what exactly. 

The sound support is currently for OSS (e.g. Linux) only. 

The VSYNC graphics given by `-V' only draw to pixel-line accuracy, rather than attempting any horizontal resolution.    


@endnode

@node sect8 "See Also"
@{i}zx81get@{ui}(1)    
@endnode

@node sect9 "Author"
Ian Collier wrote the Z80 emulation, the printer emulation, and much of the X code; I lifted it from his `xz80' Spectrum emulator. Russell Marks (rus@svgalib.org) wrote the ZX81 and ZX80 emulation and svgalib code. 


@endnode
